pigz 2.9 (29 Jun 2026) by Mr. Pong

pigz, which stands for Parallel Implementation of GZip, is a fully functional
replacement for gzip that exploits multiple processors and multiple cores to
the hilt when compressing data.

-------------------------------------------------------------------------------
NOTE: This is an ALTERED version of pigz (fork: betkub-team/pigz), not the
original distribution by Mark Adler. It is maintained to produce a static
Windows pigz.exe/unpigz.exe for the WSL VHDX backup scripts. Changes from
upstream v2.8:

  * Added --progress / --no-progress: a throttled live meter on stderr for
    both compression and decompression (input-based %, GB/GB, MB/s). stdout
    stays a pure data stream, so -c pipelines are unaffected.
  * Windows program-name detection: the executable basename is parsed across
    both '/' and '\' separators and a trailing ".exe" is stripped, so a binary
    named unpigz.exe automatically decompresses.
  * Built static against zlib-ng (zlib-compat) for runtime-dispatched AVX2
    deflate, using the mingw-w64 14-posix toolchain whose fixed winpthreads
    avoids the parallel "hang waiting on lock".

To cross-compile the Windows binaries, see the "build-pigz" skill at
.claude/skills/build-pigz/SKILL.md (full recipe), or docs/build-plan.md.
The native "make" build below is unchanged.
-------------------------------------------------------------------------------

pigz was written by Mark Adler and does not include third-party code. I am
making my contributions to and distributions of this project solely in my
personal capacity, and am not conveying any rights to any intellectual property
of any third parties.

This version of pigz is written to be portable across Unix-style operating
systems that provide the zlib and pthread libraries.

Type "make" in this directory to build the "pigz" executable.  You can then
install the executable wherever you like in your path (e.g. /usr/local/bin/).
Type "pigz" to see the command help and all of the command options.

The latest version of pigz can be found at http://zlib.net/pigz/ .  You need
zlib version 1.2.3 or later to compile pigz.  zlib version 1.2.6 or later is
recommended, which reduces the overhead between blocks.  You can find the
latest version of zlib at http://zlib.net/ .  You can look in pigz.c for the
change history.

Questions, comments, bug reports, fixes, etc. can be emailed to Mark at his
address in the license below.

